WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
Hi, I'm Alex Cookson, and I'd like to talk about the power of great datasets.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:15.600
I'd like to start off this talk by posing a question that I think all of us have asked

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:22.799
ourselves at one point, and that is, how do I learn to do this thing in R, whether that's

00:00:22.799 --> 00:00:29.200
sentiment analysis or data visualization or web scraping, how do we learn something?

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:33.919
And Alison Horst, who does a lot of wonderful illustrations about R and statistics, has

00:00:33.919 --> 00:00:41.200
one that answers this question, and it shows how teachers, mentors, and the wonderful RStats

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:46.759
community all contribute to taking someone from being a beginner to some level of proficiency

00:00:46.759 --> 00:00:48.639
with something.

00:00:48.639 --> 00:00:57.560
But I always look at this illustration and ask myself, what about great datasets?

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:01.040
Now when I say great datasets, I'm talking about something pretty specific.

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:05.360
I'm talking about datasets that are both cool and interesting.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:09.720
And when I say cool, I mean something that when you come across it, you say to yourself,

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:12.360
hey, that's cool, or that's really fun.

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:17.120
It's something that speaks to you on a deeper level, and it tends to be pretty personal.

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:20.279
So what's cool to you might not be cool to me.

00:01:20.279 --> 00:01:24.040
And when I say interesting, I mean that it rouses your curiosity.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:27.760
It makes you start asking a whole bunch of questions that you really want the answer

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:29.000
to.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.760
If you've ever played a video game where you say to yourself just five more minutes or

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:37.440
one more turn, and you're still playing it an hour later, this is the dataset version

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:38.639
of that.

00:01:38.639 --> 00:01:40.599
Just one more graph.

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:47.639
So some examples that I enjoy are the Duke Lemur Center dataset, which looks at ages

00:01:47.639 --> 00:01:51.059
and weights of almost 30 different species of lemur.

00:01:51.059 --> 00:01:58.980
The Broadway Grosses dataset, which looks at weekly box office grosses, tickets sold,

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:04.019
average top ticket prices of Broadway shows going back to 1985.

00:02:04.019 --> 00:02:08.660
And fictional character personalities, which I consider to be one of the all-time greatest

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:10.580
of great datasets.

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:15.979
And this one looks at personality traits of 800 fictional characters across over 250 different

00:02:15.979 --> 00:02:21.220
spectrums, such as the playful to serious spectrum, where we might find Michael Scott

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:26.619
from The Office on the playful side and Worf from Star Trek Next Generation way over on

00:02:26.619 --> 00:02:28.580
the serious side.

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:32.979
And I think this is such a great dataset because I've been watching so much TV and so many

00:02:32.979 --> 00:02:36.460
movies lately that when I came across it, I thought, oh, this is so fun.

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:40.460
It's something that speaks to something I've been spending a lot of my time doing.

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:45.740
And I immediately had tons and tons of questions that I wanted to ask it and uncover from this

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:47.500
dataset.

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:51.059
One of those questions was, what are some of my favorite characters' personalities?

00:02:51.059 --> 00:02:55.940
And I put in a whole bunch of work and ended up with some graphs that looked like this,

00:02:55.940 --> 00:03:01.619
which takes the six characters from Pride and Prejudice and shows their strongest traits.

00:03:01.619 --> 00:03:06.500
So we see that Elizabeth Bennett at the top left is a treasure as opposed to trash.

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:07.500
She's important.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:08.940
She has a high IQ.

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:12.300
She's independent and beautiful and a feminist.

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:16.580
But to put this together, I had to learn to do a whole bunch of things I didn't know

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:22.660
how to do before, like use custom fonts so I could get this Georgian era kind of handwriting

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:27.259
vibe, to tweak labels using the glue and ggtext packages.

00:03:27.259 --> 00:03:31.539
I had to choose an appropriate color palette for the subject matter and adjust a ton of

00:03:31.539 --> 00:03:34.979
theme elements using ggplot2.

00:03:34.979 --> 00:03:39.339
A second question I had was, which characters are most similar to or different than one

00:03:39.339 --> 00:03:40.419
another?

00:03:40.419 --> 00:03:44.179
And again, I put in a bunch of work and ended up with something like this, which looks at

00:03:44.179 --> 00:03:49.820
reasonable versus deranged characters plotted against rugged versus refined characters.

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:53.940
So here we see that characters like Sandra Clegane and Jane Cobb are really similar to

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:54.940
one another.

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:56.240
They're deranged and rugged.

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:00.860
And their opposites are Charlotte York from Sex and the City and Annie Edison, who are

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:02.880
reasonable and refined.

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:08.100
And to do this, I had to conduct principal component analysis with tidy models because

00:04:08.259 --> 00:04:10.539
these are actually principal components.

00:04:10.539 --> 00:04:11.940
You don't find them in the data.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:15.820
I had to learn to add text and arrow annotations to get this graph here.

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:19.220
And I wrote a blog post where this is an interactive chart.

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:23.579
So I had to learn how to make an interactive chart using Plotly.

00:04:23.579 --> 00:04:29.619
And if I can be honest with you for a moment, I never would have put this much effort, this

00:04:29.619 --> 00:04:33.140
many hours into analyzing Titanic passengers.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:37.980
It was because it was such a great, engaging data set where I had tons of questions that

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:42.739
I wanted the answers to that I had the drive and the curiosity to actually get those answers

00:04:42.739 --> 00:04:45.459
and learn a whole bunch of stuff in the process.

00:04:45.459 --> 00:04:48.299
So I encourage you to get your own great data sets.

00:04:48.299 --> 00:04:54.540
And to Allison, I very respectfully that we maybe add one thing to the balloon.

00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:54.940
Thank you.

